@nelgau AWESOME

IMHO an idiomatic adapter would use approximate features like topN, the "cardinality" aggregator, hyperUnique, etc, by default when possible but also support a hint to trigger an exact mode. Most of the larger Druid installations I'm aware of (including the ones at metamarkets and yahoo) make heavy use of those approximation features to keep query response time fast.

PS: Note that topN is actually exact if you are doing a lexicographic sort on the topN dimension. It's only approximate if you are sorting on a measure.

@sascha-coenen `format` is correct, we'll update the docs.

The reason for having both format-less `timeAndDims` and also actual formats like json, tsv is that the ParseSpec class is kind of overloaded to do two things. It provides a time and dimension spec (all parsers use this) and it also provides a formatter for the string parser (json/csv/tsv ‚Äì¬†only the string parser uses this).

It's okay to use one of the stringy parseSpecs like json/csv/tsv with a non-string parser, since the stringy parts will be ignored. But the timeAndDims parseSpec is simpler because it doesn't even implement the stringy parts.

@drcrallen ok, that explains why you need to do both a listObjects + getObjectDetails rather than just a listObjects.

I think the big goal is to reduce S3 costs for people using this cross-region or across the internet. https://aws.amazon.com/s3/pricing/ lists data transfer at $0.09/GB out to the internet. If people use S3 to store a 100MB lookup then fetching the lookup every 15 minutes is $26.28/month/node.

The extra HEADs should be pretty close to $0 ($0.004 per 10,000 requests + probably some data transfer for the responses), so I think we can live with them.
